-- Stocks in South Africa Rise for a Third Day; Impala, Randgold, SacOil Move
-- B y   R e n e e   B o n o r c h i s   a n d   N a s r e e n   S e r i a
-- 2010-10-12T15:56:48Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-12/south-african-stocks-decline-for-first-day-in-three-led-by-standard-bank.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  rose for the third day, adding 32.04, or 0.1
percent, to 29,779.15 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Impala Platinum Holdings Ltd.  (IMP SJ) fell for the first
time in two weeks, declining 3.40 rand, or 1.8 percent, to
190.50 rand. Platinum for immediate delivery slid as much as 0.7
percent to $1,671.80 an ounce in London.  Anglo Platinum Ltd.  (AMS SJ), the world’s largest producer
of the metal, dropped 3.02 rand, or 0.4 percent, to 697.98 rand.  Lonmin Plc  (LON SJ), the world’s third-largest platinum
producer, slipped the most in seven weeks, falling 3.78 rand, or
1.9 percent, to 193.60 rand. More than 4,000 workers will stop
work tomorrow at the Rustenburg operations of Lonmin to protest
the death of a worker in an accident.  Randgold & Exploration Co.  (RNG SJ), a mining investment
company, rose the most in four months, surging 85 cents, or 15
percent, to 6.70 rand, the highest since June 2004. The company
said it approved a payment and special dividend to shareholders
amounting to a total distribution of 310 million rand ($45
million), or 4.32 rand a share.  SacOil Holdings Ltd.  (SCL SJ), the Johannesburg-based
company with a concession in the Democratic Republic of Congo,
declined for the first day in three, dropping 1 cent, or 1.1
percent, to 92 cents. The company said it may begin
“aggressive” fundraising soon after its planned secondary
listing on London’s Alternative Investment Market early next
year.  Standard Bank Group Ltd.  (SBK SJ), Africa’s largest bank,
retreated 71 cents, or 0.7 percent, to 107.29 rand, a second day
of decreases. The lender should reveal the cost of external
contractors and help staff who will be affected by job cuts
which will be detailed on Oct. 22, according to labor union
Sasbo.  -- Editors:  Ana Monteiro ,  Vernon Wessels .  To contact the reporter on this story:
